BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:eoea9JjMMbEM7sZ4bB_ue
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260318T235001Z
DTSTART:20260328T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-28T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-28T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mT-ORgaxk_XOUTqZhgH--
SUMMARY:Restoration Event | Pioneer Park
DTSTAMP:20260318T235001Z
DTSTART:20260328T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Pioneer Park Clean Up!\n\nJoin us for a Forest Steward led wo r
	k party in Pioneer Park SE. For this work party volunteers will be removi 
	ng ivy that is blanketing the forest floor. Removing ivy helps to increase
	  the biodiversity of park by making room for native plants to sprout up. 
	I f left unchecked\, ivy will grow over our native plants and eventually p
	ull them to the ground. Your help in removing ivy will play a pivotal role
	 i n creating a healthier future for the park!\n\nNo experience necessary\
	, all ages welcome. Please note: we require participants aged 14 and under
	  to volunteer with a parent or guardian at a ratio of 1 adult to 3 kids.\
	n\nWhen: Saturday\, March 28th\, 10am-12pm\n\nWhere: Pioneer Park SE\, a m
	ap will be provided for directions to the specific work site. \n\nWhat to 
	bring : Dress for the weather in clothes you don't mind getting dirty \\(t
	hink: lo ng pants\, boots or sneakers\\). Bring water. Small snacks\, glov
	es\, and tools will be provided.\n\nRegistration: https://volunteersignup.
	org/CWRCR\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/restoration-eve
	nt-pioneer-park/18066420/2026-03-28T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civi
	c
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/restoration-event-pioneer
	-park/18066420/2026-03-28T00
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:LA9S4kOofDA9sU-vJLGxJ
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260318T235001Z
DTSTART:20260328T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	3-28T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-03-28T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:SOKbpAB-1ljmwA48xSulH
SUMMARY:Seed Starting Tips and Techniques
DTSTAMP:20260318T235001Z
DTSTART:20260328T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Taught by Nancy Kartes and Bill Thorness. Our mild late winter 
	allows us to sprout the edible garden early. Getting growing now will mean
	 longer harvests and more use of our garden throughout the year. Learn wha
	t can be started now\, whether to choose seeds or starts\, where to site y
	our early spring garden\, how to know when the soil is ready\, and how to 
	plan ahead for the best success. Hands-on lessons will also teach you how 
	to make a “seed snail\,” how to use a soil block\, and how to make your ow
	n seed-starting mix! You’ll also go home with some early-season seeds read
	y to sprout. $24.50 BBGS Member/$35 Non-Member.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcit
	y.com/events/#/details/seed-starting-tips-and-techniques/17923225/2026-03-
	28T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/seed-starting-tips-and-te
	chniques/17923225/2026-03-28T00
LOCATION:Bellevue Botanical Garden\, 12001 Main St\, Bellevue\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H30M
END:VEVENT
